<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-12-30T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-12-30T07:00:00-05:00" n="875" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d875">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/12–3044: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-12-30T15:00:00+03:00">December 30, 1944—3 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received December 30—9:12 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>5060. Molotov has sent me a draft of the additional article referred
                                to in point 6 of my 5034, December 27, 9 p.m. It reads as follows:
                                    <pb facs="0957" n="945" xml:id="pg_945"/>
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                    <p>“Article XIX. The Allied Governments consider the decision of
                                        the Vienna Arbitration Commission of November 2, 1938<note n="96" xml:id="d875fn96">
                                            <hi rend="italic">Documents on German Foreign Policy,
                                                1918–1945</hi>, series D, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 125.</note> and also the Vienna award
                                        of August 30, 1940<note n="97" xml:id="d875fn97">
                                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">x</hi>, pp. 581–587. See also telegrams 3826,
                                            August 30, 1940, from Berlin, and 509, September 6,
                                            1940, from Bucharest, <ref target="frus1940v01#pg_501">
                                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1940, vol.
                                                  <hi rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, pp. 501</ref> and
                                                <ref target="frus1940v01#pg_505">505</ref>,
                                            respectively.</note> as null and void.”</p>
                                </quote>
                            </p>
                            <p>I would appreciate instructions on this point.</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>